#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:2
msgid "Automation rules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:4
msgid ""
"Automation rules allow project maintainers to automate actions on new "
"branches, tags, and pull requests in Git repositories. If you are familiar "
"with :term:`GitOps`, this might seem familiar. The goal of automation rules "
"is to be able to control versioning and builds through your Git repository "
"and avoid duplicating these efforts on Read the Docs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:13
msgid ":doc:`/guides/automation-rules`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:14
msgid ""
"A practical guide to managing automated versioning of your documentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:16
msgid ":doc:`/versions`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:17
msgid "General explanation of how versioning works on Read the Docs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:20
msgid "How automation rules work"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:22
msgid ""
"When a new tag or branch is pushed to your repository, or a pull request is "
"opened or updated, Read the Docs receives a webhook from your Git provider. "
"Read the Docs then creates (or updates) a *version* that matches your Git "
"*tag, branch, or pull request*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:27
msgid ""
"All enabled automation rules are evaluated for that version, in the order "
"they are listed. A rule has three groups of conditions, which are checked in "
"order:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:31
msgid ""
"The version **type** must be one of the version types selected in the rule "
"(tag, branch, or pull request)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:32
msgid "The version **name** must match the version pattern in the rule."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:33
msgid ""
"If any **webhook filter** is configured, the data from the webhook event "
"(changed files, commit message, or pull request labels) must also match."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:36
msgid ""
"If all the configured conditions match, the rule's **action** is performed "
"on the version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:40
msgid ""
"Versions can match multiple automation rules, and all matching version "
"actions will be performed on the version. For build actions, only the first "
"matching rule per version triggers a build, to avoid triggering multiple "
"builds for the same change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:46
msgid "Matching the version type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:48
msgid "Each rule applies to one or more version types:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:50
msgid "**Tag** — Git tags pushed to the repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:51
msgid "**Branch** — Git branches pushed to the repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:52
msgid "**Pull request** — pull/merge requests opened against the repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:54
msgid "You can select any combination of types in a single rule."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:57
msgid "Matching the version name"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:59
msgid ""
"We have a couple predefined ways to match against the name of versions that "
"are created, and you can also define your own."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:63
msgid "Predefined matches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:65
msgid "Automation rules support two predefined version name matches:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:67
msgid "**Any version**: All new versions will match the rule."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:68
msgid ""
"**SemVer versions**: All new versions that follow `semantic versioning "
"<https://semver.org/>`__ (with or without a ``v`` prefix) will match the "
"rule."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:72
msgid "Custom matches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:74
msgid ""
"If none of the above predefined matches meet your use case, you can use a "
"**Custom match**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:77
msgid ""
"The custom match should be a valid `Python regular expression <https://docs."
"python.org/3/library/re.html>`__. Each new version's name will be tested "
"against this regular expression."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:81
msgid "Webhook filters"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:83
msgid ""
"In addition to matching the version, a rule can filter on the contents of "
"the webhook event that triggered it. Webhook filters are useful to **avoid "
"running an action when nothing relevant has changed**, for example to skip "
"builds when only non-documentation files were modified, or when the commit "
"message indicates the change should be ignored."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:89
msgid "The following filters are available:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:91
msgid "Changed files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:92
msgid ""
"Match against the list of files modified, added, or deleted in the push or "
"pull request. Patterns can include one or more of the following special "
"characters:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:95
msgid "``*`` matches everything, including slashes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:96
msgid "``?`` matches any single character."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:97
msgid "``[seq]`` matches any character in ``seq``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:99
msgid ""
"Example patterns: - ``docs/*`` matches any file under the ``docs/`` "
"directory. - ``*.md`` matches any Markdown file. - ``.readthedocs.yaml`` "
"matches the configuration file in the root of the repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:104
msgid ""
"You can specify multiple patterns, one per line. The filter matches if "
"**any** of the changed files matches **any** pattern."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:107
msgid "Commit message"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:108
msgid ""
"Match against the commit message of the push event, or the head commit of "
"the pull request, using a regular expression."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:112
msgid "Pull request labels"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:113
msgid ""
"Match against the labels of the pull request, using a regular expression. "
"This filter is only relevant for pull request events."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:117
msgid ""
"When more than one filter is configured, **all** of them must match for the "
"rule to fire."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:121
msgid ""
"Webhook filters are only available for projects connected through the :doc:"
"`GitHub App integration </reference/git-integration>`. Rules that don't use "
"webhook filters keep working with every Git provider."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:127
msgid ""
"Regular expressions are evaluated using the Python `re <https://docs.python."
"org/3/library/re.html>`__ module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:131
msgid "Actions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:133
msgid ""
"When an automation rule matches, the specified action is performed on the "
"version. Actions are split into two groups: actions that operate on the "
"version itself, and actions that trigger a build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:139
msgid "Version actions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:141
msgid "Activate version"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:142
msgid "Activates and builds the version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:144
msgid "Hide version"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:145
msgid ""
"Hides the version. If the version is not active, activates it and builds the "
"version. See :ref:`versions:Version states`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:148
msgid "Make version public"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:149
msgid ""
"Sets the version's privacy level to public. See :ref:`versions:Version "
"states`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:152
msgid "Make version private"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:153
msgid ""
"Sets the version's privacy level to private. See :ref:`versions:Version "
"states`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:156
msgid "Set version as default"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:157
msgid ""
"Sets the version as the :term:`default version`. It also activates and "
"builds the version. See :ref:`root_url_redirect`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:161
msgid "Delete version"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:162
msgid ""
"When a branch or tag is deleted from your repository, Read the Docs will "
"delete it *only if isn't active*. This action allows you to delete *active* "
"versions when a branch or tag is deleted from your repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:166
msgid "There are a couple caveats to these actions that are useful:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:168
msgid ""
"The :term:`default version` isn't deleted even if it matches a rule. You can "
"use the ``Set version as default`` action to change the default version "
"before deleting the current one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:171
msgid ""
"If your versions follow :pep:`440`, Read the Docs activates and builds the "
"version if it's greater than the current stable version. The stable version "
"is also automatically updated at the same time. See more in :doc:`versions`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:177
msgid "Build actions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:179
msgid "Trigger build for version"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:180
msgid "Trigger a build for the version when the rule matches."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:182
msgid ""
"Build actions are designed to be used together with :ref:`webhook filters "
"<automation-rules:Webhook filters>`, so that builds are only triggered when "
"something relevant has changed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:187
msgid ""
"When a project has at least one enabled rule with the **Trigger build for "
"version** action, builds are **gated** by those rules: if no build rule "
"matches the incoming webhook event, no build is triggered. If you don't have "
"any build rule configured, builds keep being triggered for every push and "
"pull request as usual."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:193
msgid "Enabling and disabling rules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:195
msgid ""
"Each rule has an **Enabled** toggle. Disabling a rule keeps its "
"configuration around but stops it from being evaluated, which is useful when "
"you want to temporarily turn off an automation without losing its "
"configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:200
msgid "Order"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../automation-rules.rst:202
msgid ""
"When a new Read the Docs version is created, all rules with a successful "
"match will have their action triggered, in the order they appear on the :"
"guilabel:`Automation Rules` page."
msgstr ""

